Work is the energy transferred to or from an object via the application of force along a displacement.
Positive Work: The force has a component in the direction of the displacement.
Negative Work: The force has a component opposite to the direction of the displacement. Both force and displacement are vectors. The work done is given by the dot product of the two vectors, where the result is a scalar. The work can be given by line integrals: W = \int _C \vec {F} \cdot d\vec {r} where d\vec {r} is the tiny displacement vector along the path C. For motion along a straight line, we have a degenerated case of the line integral: W = \vec {F} \cdot \vec {r}
